8","about 1286":"omkring 1286","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1260–":"circa 1260–Overleden","1260–Female":"1260–Overleden","1259–Male":"1259–Overleden","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1286–Male":"1286–Overleden","1241–Male":"1241–Overleden","1240–Female":"1240–Overleden","about 1260":"circa 1260","1337":"1337","about 1280":"circa 1280","1259":"1259","about 1259":"circa 1259","1286":"1286","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","about 1278":"circa 1278","about 1286":"circa 1286","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1260–":"about 1260–Deceased","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1259–Male":"1259–Deceased","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1286–Male":"1286–Deceased","1241–Male":"1241–Deceased","1240–Female":"1240–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","1337":"1337","about 1280":"about 1280","1259":"1259","about 1259":"about 1259","1286":"1286","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","about 1278":"about 1278","about 1286":"about 1286","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beauchamp was born about 1260, in Monmouthshire, Wales, her father, Andrew de Beauchamp, was 21 and her mother, Mrs Andrew Beauchamp, was 22. She married Sir Edward de Kemeys about 1278, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1259–Male":"1259–Surnud","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1241–Male":"1241–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1337":"1337","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1259":"1259","about 1259":"umbes 1259","1286":"1286","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","about 1278":"umbes 1278","about 1286":"umbes 1286","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1259–Male":"1259–Kuollut","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1241–Male":"1241–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1337":"1337","about 1280":"noin 1280","1259":"1259","about 1259":"noin 1259","1286":"1286","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","about 1278":"noin 1278","about 1286":"noin 1286","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1260–":"environ 1260–Décédée","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1259–Male":"1259–Décédé","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1286–Male":"1286–Décédé","1241–Male":"1241–Décédé","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","about 1260":"environ 1260","1337":"1337","about 1280":"environ 1280","1259":"1259","about 1259":"environ 1259","1286":"1286","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","about 1278":"environ 1278","about 1286":"environ 1286","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Saint Mellons, Monmouthshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Beauchamp est née environ 1260, à Monmouthshire, Galles, son père, Andrew de Beauchamp, avait 21 ans et 